-- в”Ђв”Ђ ResourceSpace в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$ResourceSpace is an open-source digital asset management (DAM) system that can be self-hosted for free or run as a managed cloud service by its maintainer, Montala.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free open-source self-hosted; paid managed cloud hosting tiers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted, or free cloud tier with 10GB/10 users); paid cloud plans start around $358/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2006, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small team; maintainer Montala Limited is 100% employee-owned$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Watchfield, Oxfordshire, United Kingdom$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$ResourceSpace Review 2026: Open-Source DAM Pricing and Features$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$ResourceSpace is a free, open-source digital asset management system with optional managed cloud hosting. Compare 2026 pricing, features and FAQs.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$ResourceSpace is an open-source digital asset management (DAM) system originally created in 2006 by developers Dan Huby and Neale Hall while working as contractors for the charity Oxfam, which needed a better way to organize its media library than the expensive, clunky DAM tools available at the time; Oxfam subsequently released the software under an open-source license, and Huby went on to found Montala Limited, the UK company that now maintains ResourceSpace, provides professional services, and hosts the managed cloud version. Montala is headquartered in Watchfield, Oxfordshire, in the UK, is 100% employee-owned, operates as a certified B Corporation, and holds ISO 27001 certification and UK Crown Commercial Service supplier status. Because ResourceSpace is open source, there is no software license fee for self-hosting: organizations can download and run the full DAM platform on their own servers at no cost, with no per-user restrictions, and charges only apply to optional paid support or the managed cloud offering. For teams that don't want to self-host, ResourceSpace offers a free cloud tier with 10GB of storage and up to 10 users, plus paid cloud hosting tiers hosted in London Docklands data centers: Team Cloud around $358/month, roughly $5,108/year, for 25 users and 1-9TB storage; Business Cloud around $778/month, roughly $11,500/year, for 100 users plus optional public access and 3-15TB storage; Enterprise Cloud around $1,357/month, roughly $20,355/year, for 500 users, 8-20TB storage, and priority support; and a custom-quoted Platinum Cloud tier for unlimited users and 50TB-plus storage. All paid cloud tiers include AI-assisted tools such as automatic tagging, face detection, and natural-language search, along with SSO, API access, SFTP drop folders, a test or staging instance, and a dedicated server. ResourceSpace is used by universities, charities, museums, marketing teams, and enterprises to centrally store, tag, search, and control access to images, video, and documents, and it supports metadata schemas, watermarking, usage rights tracking, and integration via its open API. Its combination of a genuinely free, unrestricted open-source core with an optional fully managed hosting path distinguishes it from most commercial DAM vendors, such as Bynder or Widen, which are exclusively closed-source SaaS products with per-user licensing.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '00400667-6209-4172-b7aa-b8106d654692';

